h centuries, too late to have had much influence on surname formationm in Britain, except in Wales."],"variants":[{"name":"Amoss","meanings":["English: variant of   Amos  ."]},{"name":"Amis","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Ames  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"David Amos was born in 1400, in Downton, Hampshire, England as the son of Amos. He married Nancy Watkins in Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died after 1420, in England."},"et":{"1400–Aft 1420":"1400–pärast 1420","1400–1420":"1400–1420","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","Aft 1420":"pärast 1420","1470":"1470","1380":"1380","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Downton, Hampshire, England":"Downton, Hampshire, England","Bramford, Suffolk, England":"Bramford, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1400–Aft 1420":"1400–1420 jälkeen","1400–1420":"1400–1420","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1400":"1400","1420":"1420","Aft 1420":"1420 jälkeen","1470":